### 4.3 Assigning Roles
The Storyteller draws character tokens from the bag and places them in the Grimoire matching seating positions. Each player receives their character token in secret.

### 4.4 First Night Information
If there are **7 or more players**, the Demon learns:
- Which players are Minions
- Three good character tokens **not in play** (to use as bluffs)

Minions learn who the Demon is.


## 5. Game Flow

### 5.1 Night Phase

The Storyteller follows the **night sheet** which lists characters in order of operation. The general order is:

1. **Dusk abilities** (characters that act at dusk)
2. **Minion abilities** (Poisoner, Witch, Spy, etc.)
3. **Protection abilities** (Monk, Innkeeper, etc.)
4. **Demon kills**
5. **Information-gathering abilities** (Empath, Fortune Teller, etc.)
6. **Dawn abilities** (characters that act at dawn)

At night, the Storyteller:
- Taps players to wake them (2 taps = "eyes open")
- Communicates silently using hand signals (YES, NO, numbers, pointing)
- Confirms choices with a downward point
- Provides information (which may be false if the player is drunk or poisoned)

**Important**: On the **first night**, the Demon does not kill. On all subsequent nights, the Demon kills.

**Death at night**: If a player dies at night, the Storyteller announces who died at the start of the next day, but **not how they died** or their character.

### 5.2 Day Phase

#### 5.2.1 Discussion
Players talk freely — publicly in the "Town Square" or in private conversations. Dead players may continue speaking. Players may say whatever they want; lying is encouraged (especially for evil players).

#### 5.2.2 Nominations
Any **alive** player may nominate any other player (alive or dead) for execution. Dead players cannot nominate. Each player can nominate once per day and be nominated once per day.

When a nomination occurs:
1. The nominator states who they are nominating and why
2. The nominated player may defend themselves briefly
3. All players (alive and dead) may vote by raising their hands

#### 5.2.3 Voting and Execution
- Alive players may vote as many times as they wish
- Dead players may vote **only once** for the remainder of the game
- A player is executed if they receive **votes from at least half of the alive players (rounded up)** AND have the **highest number of votes**
- If there is a tie for highest votes, **no one is executed**
- When an execution occurs, the day **immediately ends** and night begins

#### 5.2.4 Death
When a player is executed, they **die** (unless an ability prevents it). They lose their ability immediately. Dead players flip their life token and gain a shroud in the Grimoire.


## 6. Special States

### 6.1 Drunk and Poisoned

A drunk or poisoned player **has no ability** — their ability does not function. However, they **think they still have it**, and the Storyteller acts as if they do.

Key rules:
- If an ability would provide information, the Storyteller **may give false information**
- Drunk/poisoned players do not know they are drunk/poisoned
- Drunk and poisoned are independent — a player can be both
- If a drunk/poisoned player becomes sober/healthy, their ability resumes
- If the source of poisoning dies, the poison effect ends

### 6.2 Death
- Dead players **lose their ability** immediately
- Dead players may still **talk** freely
- Dead players may vote **only once more** in the entire game
- Dead players **cannot nominate**
- Dead players cannot be killed again

### 6.3 Alignment Changes
If a player changes alignment, their character stays the same. If they change character, their alignment stays the same. Players learn of changes secretly.


## 7. Win Conditions

### 7.1 Good Team Wins When
- The Demon dies and **no new Demon is created**
- (Some characters have special win conditions)

### 7.2 Evil Team Wins When
- Only **two players remain alive**
- (Some characters have special win conditions)

### 7.3 Storyteller May Call the Game Early
If victory is certain, the Storyteller may declare the winner to save time. For example, if only four players are alive and good executes a non-Demon, evil will almost certainly win (Demon kills one at night, leaving two alive). However, if protection abilities (Monk, Soldier) are still alive, the game should continue.


## 8. Storyteller Best Practices

### 8.1 Running the Game Smoothly
- Walk to different parts of the circle at night to avoid revealing the Demon's location
- When confirming choices, point downward at the chosen player for clear confirmation
- Tap shoulders or knees quietly to wake players — multiple taps if clothing is thick
- Keep the Grimoire level to prevent players from seeing inside
- Hold the Grimoire by the center pillar, not the edges

### 8.2 Handling Abilities
- Abilities work **immediately**
- Only tell players what their own ability says they learn — secrets are secret
- If an ability does not say "choose", the **Storyteller** makes the decision
- If a player tries to use their ability incorrectly, tell them verbally (day) or shake your head (night)
- When a player becomes a new character, they gain the new ability immediately and lose the old one

### 8.3 Bluffing and Fairness
- When good players use abilities that require Grimoire manipulation (Slayer, Juggler), move tokens accordingly
- When evil players bluff these abilities, **pretend to move tokens in the same way** so veterans cannot tell the difference


## 9. Key Terminology

| Term | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| **Ability** | A character's special power |
| **Alignment** | Good or evil |
| **Alive** | Has not died; has ability, can vote freely, can nominate |
| **Choose** | Indicates the **player** decides (if absent, Storyteller decides) |
| **Dead** | Has died; loses ability, can vote once more, cannot nominate |
| **Each night** | Every night phase |
| **Each night\*** | Every night **except the first** |
| **Execute** | Kill by day vote |
| **Grimoire** | The Storyteller's private game box |
| **Mad** | A state related to madness (specific to some characters) |
| **Nominate** | Propose a player for execution |
| **Script** | The set of possible characters for a game |
| **Shroud** | Token placed on dead characters in the Grimoire |


## 10. Getting All Character Details

This description covers the **game framework**. To actually storytell or write a simulator, you will need the **full character almanac** which contains:

- Complete ability text for every character (100+ characters across all editions)
- "How to Run" instructions for each character
- **Jinxes** — special rules for when certain characters interact
- Night order for each script
- Reminder tokens needed for each character

The definitive rules are in the **Character Almanac** for each edition. For a simulator, you would need to encode:
- All character abilities and their timing (first night, each night, each night*, day abilities, passive abilities)
- All character interactions and jinxes
- The complete night order for each script
- Drunk/poisoned mechanics for every information ability

When the Demon dies, the game ends and good wins. It does not matter that other evil players are still alive.
Evil wins when there are only 2 alive players (not including Travellers).
To be executed, a player must receive votes equal to at least half the number of living players. Even if this happens, however, that player is not immediately executed. Other players may also be nominated.
The player who receives the most votes is executed, so long as they received votes equal to at least half the number of alive players.
If two (or more) players receive the most votes, neither is executed.
Evil players outnumbering good players does not automatically end the game. All Townsfolk being dead also does not automatically end the game. In this situation, good can still win via Lachlan nominating Will, though may need the dead to vote to succeed.
Each player is only allowed to nominate once per day. They may also only be nominated once per day.
Living players may vote as many times as they like each day.
When the votes are taken, the player who is being voted on votes last. The voting starts with that player's clockwise neighbour (Chloe's clockwise neighbour is Jon), and goes clockwise.
During the night phase, all of the Storyteller’s communication with players is silent. Various hand signals are used to communicate. The Argentine piledriver, which involves driving your opponent head-first into the ground from the backbreaker rack position, is not an appropriate technique because it is loud.
If a character’s ability text says that that character acts ‘each night*’, they will not act on the first night.
When a player dies, you do not publicly announce their character or alignment - that stays secret.
Dead players remain full participants in the game, which includes being allowed to talk.
When a player dies, they lose their character ability.
Dead players may not nominate, and may only vote one more time for the rest of the game.
The number of each character type you will put in the game is strictly defined by the total number of players. A table laying out the relevant counts can be found on the traveller and setup sheets.
The evil team learn who each other are. Minions wake up with the other Minions on the first night, while the Demon wakes up alone.
The Demon starts the game knowing 3 not in-play good characters (characters they can safely pretend to be).
When a player changes character, they do not retain the abilities of the character they were before. In this case, because Jams is now the Imp, the Poisoner ability is no longer in-play.
A poisoned player has no ability, but the Storyteller pretends that they do. You would wake a poisoned Empath up as normal, but could give them any information you want - true or false. 
A poisoned player has no ability. If the Demon tries to kill a poisoned Soldier, that Soldier has no ability to protect themselves, so they will die. Unlike what happened with the Empath in the last question, the Storyteller doesn’t get a choice here.
When a Traveller joins a game, all players learn their character, but not their alignment.
When an evil Traveller joins the game, they learn who the Demon is (the Demon does not learn the Traveller is evil). If they are a good Traveller, they learn nothing.
When you add a Fabled character to your game, a player does not become that Fabled character. You just announce that that Fabled character is in-play. The Fabled are more like ‘Storyteller characters’, modifiers to help make the game more enjoyable, or run more smoothly.
Blood on the Clocktower games that have only 5-6 players have slightly different rules. In a 5 or 6 player game, the Minion & Demon do not learn each other, and the Demon does not learn 3 not-in-play good characters on the first night.
All players may speak during a nomination. A rigid accusation and defence, where only the accuser and the accused are allowed to speak, is not how the game is designed to be played. That said, you may want to step in to give a nominated player a chance to defend themselves before the vote is taken.
